<section id="why-i-built-rootspec" data-test="authors-notes" style="padding:5rem 1.5rem;background:var(--color-bg);">
  <div style="max-width:48rem;margin:0 auto;">
    <h2 data-test="authors-notes-heading" style="font-size:clamp(1.5rem,4vw,2.25rem);font-weight:700;margin:0 0 1.75rem;color:var(--color-text);">Why I Built RootSpec</h2>

    <p style="font-size:1.05rem;color:var(--color-text-muted);line-height:1.75;margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
      Most thinking about AI in software development focuses on the wrong constraint. We obsess over whether the model can write correct code — and it can, increasingly well. But correctness alone isn't the bottleneck. The bottleneck is intent transmission: how do you reliably convey what you actually want, at sufficient fidelity, so that an autonomous agent produces what you intended rather than what it inferred?
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:1.05rem;color:var(--color-text-muted);line-height:1.75;margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
      The replicator from Star Trek is instructive here. The magic isn't the matter synthesizer — it's the pattern buffer. Without a precise, complete pattern, you don't get Earl Grey tea; you get something approximately tea-shaped that may or may not be drinkable. The synthesizer is the easy part. The pattern is the hard part.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:1.05rem;color:var(--color-text-muted);line-height:1.75;margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
      I built RootSpec because I kept running into the same failure mode: I'd describe what I wanted, the agent would build something plausible, and then I'd spend more time correcting the wrong decisions than I would have spent building it myself. The spec wasn't the problem — the absence of a shared, testable spec was the problem.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:1.05rem;color:var(--color-text-muted);line-height:1.75;margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
      RootSpec is an attempt to formalize the pattern buffer. It gives agents a structured, hierarchical specification they can read, validate against, and implement from — in order, with tests, with checkpoints. It's not a prompt template. It's a methodology: a way of working that makes agent-produced software auditable by design.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:1.05rem;color:var(--color-text-muted);line-height:1.75;margin:0;">
      Generating code is now trivial. Validating that the generated code matches intent — at every level, from philosophy to interaction detail — is the unsolved problem. RootSpec is my attempt at solving it.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
